            ContentJson = """
{"body":"## Reading Job Cost — Estimate vs. Actual\n\nThe **Cost Analysis** section in a job's details is where a PM, estimator, or plant manager checks whether a job is running to plan or running over. It compares what you estimated against what the job has actually cost so far, in four buckets:\n\n- **Material** — the stock and raw material going into the job.\n- **Labor** — the hours clocked against the job.\n- **Burden** (overhead) — your shop rate applied to those hours: machine time, utilities, and other indirect costs.\n- **Subcontract** — work you sent outside, like plating or heat-treat.\n\nEach bucket shows the estimate, the actual, and the difference between them — the **variance**. A positive variance means the job has run over its estimate on that bucket; a negative one means it's coming in under. The bottom line pulls it together against the price you quoted, so you can see the job's actual margin as it stands. Numbers refresh when you reopen the section, so what you see reflects the latest time and material posted. Use this mid-job to catch a job bleeding money while you can still act — pull ahead on labor, chase a material overrun, or flag the quote as under-priced for next time. Shop-wide profitability (every job's quote vs. actual) lives in its own report, not on this per-job section.\n\n### Issuing and Returning Material\n\nActual material cost comes from the material you **issue** to the job. From the job you can post three kinds of movement:\n\n- **Issue** — consume stock onto the job. This is the normal case: you pull material from a bin and charge it to the job.\n- **Return** — put unused stock back. If you issued too much, return the remainder so the job isn't charged for material it never used.\n- **Scrap** — write off material that was spoiled or cut wrong. It stays charged to the job but doesn't go back to stock.\n\nEach movement records the part, quantity, unit cost, and the lot it came from, plus who posted it and when — so a job carries full traceability of what material it consumed. If a part is stored in more than one place, you pick the bin or location you're pulling from. The job's actual material cost is simply what you issued, minus what you returned, minus scrap, valued at cost. Being disciplined here — issuing what you pull and returning what you don't — is what keeps the Material bucket honest.\n\n## Tying a Job to a Sales-Order Line\n\nWhen you create a job for a customer order, you can tie it straight to the **sales-order line** it fulfills. The picker lists open order lines — order number, line, part, description, and quantity — so you can point the job at exactly the line it's building. Each line also shows how many open jobs already point at it. Lines that already have a job are **hidden by default** so you don't accidentally start a second job against a line that's already covered; flip on \"show assigned\" if you genuinely need to add another. Tying the job to the line keeps the order and the shop-floor work in step: when the job ships, the order knows that line is done.\n\n## Building to an Older BOM — the Stale Warning\n\nWhen you release a job against a part, the job locks onto the **bill of materials in effect that day**. That's on purpose: the job builds to the recipe it was released with, even if engineering revises the part later. So a job in progress isn't quietly re-planned out from under the floor.\n\nThe trade-off is that a long-running job can fall behind the current design. The details panel compares the revision the job was released against with the part's latest revision. If the part's BOM has moved on since release, you'll see a **stale warning** — this job is building to an older BOM. That's a decision point for a planner or engineer: is the change minor enough to let the job finish as-is, or does it need to be re-released to the newer BOM? The warning never changes the job for you; it just tells you the two no longer match so you can make the call.\n\n## Releasing a Job to the Floor\n\nCreating a job with **New Job** is the moment planning hands work to the floor — it releases the job so operators can clock onto it and start building. Because it's a release, not everyone gets the button: it's for planners, PMs, engineers, managers, office managers, and production workers. If your shop doesn't run jobs through Forge at all, the New Job button won't appear — that's a setup choice, not a permission you're missing.\n\n## Cover Photos and the Incomplete-Profile Warning\n\n**Cover photo** — the camera button at the top of a job's details sets the picture that shows across the top of the card on the board. It points at a file you've **already attached** to the job, so upload the photo to the job's Files first, then pick it as the cover. Handy for putting a part photo or a marked-up drawing right on the board card.\n\n**Incomplete-profile assignee warning** — in the Assignee dropdown, a person who hasn't finished setting up their profile shows a ⚠ and \"(incomplete profile).\" You can still assign them — the warning is just a heads-up. It matters because that person may not be able to clock in or run floor work until their onboarding and required forms are done, so a job assigned to them can stall until they're set up.","sections":[]}
"""
